 Special training for Indian coaches
A STAFF REPORTERCalcutta: Four English Premier League (EPL) coaches will train 80 young Indian coaches over a period of three years. The programme will be conducted under the Premier Skills  a project by the EPL, the AIFF, the IFA and supported by the SAI Eastern Centre and DPS (RK Puram). The panel of coaches will be headed by Warren Barton  the head coach of EPL, a former England and Newcastle United player  and Robby Earle. The training will start in February 2008, with the first two sessions scheduled in New Delhi (February 4-9) and Calcutta (March 10-15). Having successfully implemented the project in Egypt earlier this year, we thought of India as football is a big sport here besides cricket and hockey Well try and develop their coaching abilities by making the foundation strong, Barton told reporters at a press conference on Thursday. The participants will be selected jointly by the IFA, the SAI and British Council. 
